{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0502ab82-f355-4c41-bd5d-21c339e0e623","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer workload versions that your updated SDK requires.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → `dotnet workload update`. Installation is broken/corrupt → `dotnet workload repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after updating, you can also try restoring workloads from your project:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36172e93-6512-408e-abd3-c8476ff30832","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":260},"id":"2766efb5-579f-420a-93f5-ff6037b9ccbf","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:45:02.566Z","parentId":"c5664806-84ba-40fc-ba8a-8b4c2f8384cc"}
